SIMPLE: forsooth
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Forsooth
<hw>For*sooth"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>fors⟦omac⟧⟦edh⟧</ets>; <ets>for</ets>, prep. +
<ets>s⟦omac⟧⟦edh⟧</ets> sooth, truth. See <er>For</er>,
<ets>prep</ets>., and <er>Sooth</er>.]</ety> <def>In truth; in fact;
certainly; very well; -- formerly used as an expression of deference or
respect, especially to woman; now used ironically or
contemptuously.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A fit man, <qex>forsooth</qex>, to govern a realm!</q>
<rj><qau>Hayward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our old English word <qex>forsooth</qex> has been changed for the
French <qex>madam</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Guardian.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Forsooth</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Forsooth
<hw>For*sooth"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To address respectfully with
the term <xex>forsooth</xex>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The captain of the ⟦ldquo⟧Charles⟦rdquo⟧ had <qex>forsoothed</qex>
her, though he knew her well enough and she him.</q>
<rj><qau>Pepys.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Forsooth</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Forsooth
<hw>For*sooth"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A person who used
<xex>forsooth</xex> much; a very ceremonious and deferential
person.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You sip so like a <qex>forsooth</qex> of the city.</q> <rj><qau>B.
Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Forspeak</ent>⟦br⟧
